Mar. 24, 1964: A cab was hailed for Reluctant Bootsie, a baby Indian elephant that handlers feared wouldn’t make the five-mile march to Madison Square Garden from the Mott Haven railyards. As the article explained, Bootsie, a teething Barnum and Bailey Circus elephant, was taken in and out of the cab for the benefit of photographers, then driven a few yards. The ride was canceled when Hugo Schmitt, Bootsie’s trainer, “detected signs of nervousness in the elephant.”